      "content": "thanks for that. it passed my tests but i'm worried it might be too specific to those cases. like, what happens if the amounts are bigger? or if the pattern is slightly different?\n\nmy manager just sent over a few more edge cases to make sure the logic is actually robust and not just checking for small amounts. can you update the function so it also handles these?\n\n```python\nadditional_tests = [\n    # Case 4: Higher amounts, but still multiple small-ish ones\n    # (e.g., 600, 700, 800 might be smurfing if the threshold is meant to be higher)\n    {'transactions': [\n        {'amount': 600, 'sender': 'X', 'receiver': 'Y'},\n        {'amount': 700, 'sender': 'X', 'receiver': 'Y'},\n        {'amount': 650, 'sender': 'X', 'receiver': 'Y'}\n    ], 'expected': True},\n\n    # Case 5: Exactly 2 transactions, but one is very large\n    {'transactions': [\n        {'amount': 100, 'sender': 'Z', 'receiver': 'W'},\n        {'amount': 5000, 'sender': 'Z', 'receiver': 'W'}\n    ], 'expected': False},\n\n    # Case 6: Lots of transactions, but different receivers\n    {'transactions': [\n        {'amount': 100, 'sender': 'A', 'receiver': 'B'},\n        {'amount': 100, 'sender': 'A', 'receiver': 'C'},\n        {'amount': 100, 'sender': 'A', 'receiver': 'D'}\n    ], 'expected': False}\n]\n\n# combine with previous and run\nall_tests = test_cases + additional_tests\ndef run_tests(func):\n    for i, test in enumerate(all_tests):\n        result = func(test['transactions'])\n        assert result == test['expected'], f\"Test {i} failed: expected {test['expected']}, got {result}\"\n    print(\"All tests passed!\")\n```",
